Venus is the second planet from the sun, and roughly the same size as Earth. Unlike Earth, however, Venus has a thick toxic atmosphere that traps heat within it. As a result, temperatures on Venus can reach up to 880 degrees Fahrenheit. That’s hot enough to melt lead!
Venus is the hottest planet in our solar system. With an atmosphere that’s 96% carbon dioxide, dense clouds within Venus’ atmosphere are composed of sulphuric acid and other corrosive compounds.
Only two man-made spacecrafts have penetrated it’s atmosphere. In fact, very few objects in general seem to be able to get through the thick, acidic atmosphere- including asteroids and meteorites. Much of Venus’ surface is marked with volcanoes and deep canyons. The biggest canyon is over 4,000 miles long!
Much like Mercury, Venus doesn’t have a moon of its own. It takes 225 Earth days to revolve around the Sun, and 116 Earth days for one day on Venus. Venus is named after the Roman God of love, and the only planet in our solar system to have been named after a woman. You may also know the God of love by her Greek name, Aphrodite.
